<tr>
<td>
<img alt="" height="" src="/common/images/cal-phylo.jpg">
</td>
<td>
<!-- 2017-10-30 -->
<!-- October 30, 2017 -->
<p align="center"><blockquote class="pageMajorHeading">
<span class="copyrightText">October 30, 2017</span><br />
A second paper has been published by the same UC/JEPS team referenced in a previous news item on this page (April 11, 2017), adding phylogenetic methods to the study of diversity and endemism in the California flora. This novel "spatial phylogenetics" approach makes it possible to evaluate biodiversity from an evolutionary standpoint, including discovering significant areas of neo- and paleo-endemism. Read the <a href="http://news.berkeley.edu/2017/12/04/californias-dry-regions-are-hotspots-of-plant-diversity/">campus news story here</a> and the <a href="https://bmcbiol.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12915-017-0435-x">open-source paper here.</a></blockquote></td>
	<td>
<!--<img alt="" height="" src="/common/images/cal-phylo.jpg">-->
	</td>
</tr>
